<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler-Benz Denies Interest in Buying Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- German Daimler-Benz said today it
was at the moment not interested in buying the prestigious British
luxury marque Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
"A purchase of this nature is not an issue at the moment," said a
spokesman of Daimler-Benz, parent company of carmaker
Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
The denial came after the news magazine Der Spiegal said the
Stuttgart-based firm was competing with Munich-based luxury carmaker
BMW to buy up Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
The Vickers industrial group, the British parent company of
Rolls-Royce, announced its sale of Rolls-Royce last Monday. So
far, BMW, Ford and Ferrari have expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
BMW is already producing engines for Rolls-Royce. According to
Spiegal, BMW thought the price of 400 million pounds demanded by
Vickers was too high.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Spiegal to go on sale Monday quoted Daimler
passenger car board member Juergen Hubbert as saying: "We want our
bid to succeed, Rolls-Royce fits in with our concept."
</P>
<P>
According to him, Daimler-Benz has not yet examined in detail
purchasing Rolls-Royce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
