<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT November 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin left here Saturday
morning for Boston to continue his nine-day state visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is expected to deliver a speech at the Harvard University
in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president flew to New York from Philadelphia
Thursday evening. During his short stay in New York, Jiang met
former U.S. president George Bush and former secretary of state
Henry Kissinger. (US-Jiang-Boston)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto approved a plan on bilateral
cooperation in politics, economy and finance during their meeting
Saturday, said the Russian President's Press Secretary Sergei
Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, who started Saturday an informal weekend
summit, also exchanged views on the general idea of developing
Russian-Japanese relations during a four-hour boat trip down the
Yeniser River. (Japan-Russia-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and his
visiting French counterpart Lionel Jospin criticized Baghdad on
Friday for banning Americans from taking part in the United
Nations arms inspection teams in Iraq. They described the move as
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers said in a joint statement that they
supported the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
proposal to send a special committee to Baghdad to make the
oil-rich Arab state cooperate with the U. N. inspection
teams. (Russia-France-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano and Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic will meet during the Balkan
countries' summit scheduled for November 2-4 in Greece, local
reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, announced by Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo
on Friday, will be the first of its kind since former Albanian
Prime Minister Enver Hoxha and former Yugoslav leader Tito met in
Belgrade in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Albania and Yugoslavia have been involved in disputes for
nearly half a century, especially over the issue of Albanians in
Yugoslavia's Kosovo. (Albania-Yugoslavia-Meet) 
</P>
</TEXT>
