<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Doha Conference Meaningless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak said here today that it is meaningless to convene the
Middle East and North Africa Economic Conference in Qatar next
month as Israel sticks to its hardline policies.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the UAE Television, the Egyptian
president also made clear before he concluded his two-day visit to
the United Arab Emirates, that Egypt will not quickly make its
last words on its participation.
</P>
<P>
If there is tangible progress in the Middle East peace
process, the Egyptian president said that "it will be encouraging
for (Egypt's) participation in the conference."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the remarks after Qatar said the conference will
"give new impetus" to the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that he "do not think any significance at all for
the economic conference because of Israel's current rejection of
respecting what it agreed (with Arabs)."
</P>
<P>
He said the conference, the fourth since it was initiated in
1994, had been affective to the Middle East peace process, but
that was in cases of the Arab-Israeli peace talks were kept on
track.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president explained that Israeli former Prime
Minister Shimon Peres adopted the idea of attending the conference
in a bid to support the peace process which had been kept moving
when Israel signed with Arabs the Oslo agreement and agreed to
return some cities to the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
"The conference launched in Casablanca and then held
separately in Amman and Cairo when the Middle East peace process
had been stepping on track," he stated.
</P>
<P>
"We will await until the last minute to see what will happen
during the meeting which is to be held between the Palestinians and
Israelis in Washington on Monday," he said on possible Egyptian
participation of the conference.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the United States will agree together with Israel to
implement the agreements (signed) with the Palestinians," said the
Egyptian president.
</P>
<P>
The conference, traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel
and their major partners in the other parts of the world, has
been boycotted by some of Arab states such as Syria, Lebanon, the
Palestinian National Authority, the UAE and Saudi Arabia due to
Israel's appearance.
</P>
<P>
The countries said that Israel should not be given chances
to benefit from the economic conference.
</P>
<P>
Qatar argued that they considered the conference will "give
new impetus to the Middle East peace process and advance
economic development in the region."
</P>
<P>
Doha has sent invitations to 92 countries and international
organizations in the world and so far more than 50 countries
from Europe, Asia and America have promised their participation.
</P>
<P>
Among the countries, the United States, Israel and the European
countries will send delegations at the ministerial level. Israeli
Foreign Minister Levy and the U.S. Secretary of State Albright
will represent their countries in the conference.
</P>
<P>
Doha has not mentioned the participating Arab states. Observers
here said that Jordan and Yemen are the only two Arab countries
who have confirmed their appearance while most of the others
remain hesitate to make their last words. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
