<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's First Lady Calls for National AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Ministry of Health
and Child Welfare has been challenged to expedite the
introduction of an AIDS policy to help curb the rapid spread of
HIV.
</P>
<P>
The challenge by First Lady Grace Mugabe in a speech read on
her behalf during a dinner dance hosted by the AIDS Counseling
Trust came in the wake of reports of victimization of people with
AIDS due to lack of a clear-cut policy.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of policy leads to confusion, exploitation and
victimization of people living with AIDS," said the first lady.
</P>
<P>
Some 10 percent of Zimbabwe's 12.4 million population is
estimated to be infected with the AIDS-causing HIV. Experts say
most of the affected are in the productive age group.
</P>
<P>
She said there should be attempts to save children from the
scourge in order to break the pandemic and ensure an AIDS-free
generation.
</P>
<P>
She castigated adults who sexually abused children and in the
process infected them with venereal diseases including HIV.
</P>
<P>
She said, "we need to focus intensely our HIV/AIDS prevention
program toward the uninfected age group, namely, those children
between five to 15 years and ensure that they enter adulthood
free of infection."
</P>
<P>
The law, she said, should be harsh with sexual perverts who
abused children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
