<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Employees' Quality of Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Industrial relations and the
quality of life of employees have been drastically eroded in
countries undergoing structural adjustment programs (SAPs), the
Zimbabwe Industrial Relations Association (ZIRA) said today.
</P>
<P>
ZIRA Secretary Arnold Sibanda said here that the disturbing
fact about SAPs is an erosion of the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
"Evidence we are getting is that SAPs have caused a lot of
suffering among people. If they have achieved growth here and
there this has not translated generally into improvement of the
quality of life of the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ZIRA held its second congress which focused on industrial
relations and structural adjustment programs in Africa this week.
</P>
<P>
He said the congress's assessment of the impact, shortfalls of
SAPs and the role of actors in industrial related fields was
timely.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to take stock of effects of the program on
industrial relations. By industrial relations we mean employees,
the unemployed, under-employed, employers and administration,"
said Sibanda.
</P>
<P>
He said phasing out of SAPs is not the issue but the content,
design, implementation and monitoring of programs remain.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, he said, should learn from experiences of other
African countries and experts on industrial relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Mutual Understanding Between China, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOSTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang
Zemin today called for enhancing mutual understanding between
China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at Harvard University, Jiang said it would
be impossible for countries to build trust and promote cooperation
with each other without mutual understanding which is the basis
for state-to-state relations.
</P>
<P>
"Since the establishment of diplomatic ties between China and
the United States, the exchanges and mutual understanding between
our two peoples have broadened and deepened steadily," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, this is not enough," he noted. To promote the
development of China-U.S. relations, China needs to know the
United States better and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
The friendly exchanges between the Chinese and American peoples
date back to more than two hundred years ago, he said. Many
Chinese contributed to the nation-building of the United States,
while a lot of American friends helped and supported the national
liberation cause of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"We will never forget their contribution which has touched us
deeply," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit to IBM, AT&AMP;T and the Bell laboratory
Friday gave him some first-hand knowledge of the latest
successes in modern science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"In our course to further open up and achieve modernization, we
have spared no efforts in learning from all the fine cultural
achievements of the American people," he added.
</P>
<P>
To know China better, it is important to approach China from a
historical and cultural perspective because China is a country
with 5,000 years of civilization, the Chinese president noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of Harvard University's efforts on China
studies, Jiang said: "In order to promote the study of China's
past and present, I will present Harvard with a set of newly
published Twenty-Four Histories with Mao Zedong's Comments."
</P>
<P>
Twenty-Four Histories are important classical works on China's
history of several thousand years.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that Harvard is among the first American
universities to accept Chinese students. The Chinese educational,
scientific and cultural communities have all along maintained
academic exchanges with Harvard.
</P>
<P>
"Harvard has thus made useful contribution to the enhanced
mutual understanding between the Chinese and American peoples," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is on a nine-day state visit to the United States, the
first by a Chinese head of state in 12 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
