<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intensified Trade with DRC Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of Zimbabwe
Industries (CZI) has called for more trade and investment
missions to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) by combined
government and private sector delegations.
</P>
<P>
CZI President Jomee Blanchfield today said this is necessary
in order to understand the business culture of the people there
and to explore new avenues for trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
"We need to make a determined effort through fiscal support
for firms participating in such activities. We know there are
fiscal constraints at present, but the benefits will outweigh the
immediate fiscal difficulties. We should go for it," she said.
</P>
<P>
Blanchfield urged the business community to be more aggressive
in its quest for entry into the DRC market.
</P>
<P>
Some business people, she said, have already been to the DRC
to explore opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The CZI official said they should however be wary of the fact
that this is a new venture and in many cases the results will
take time to positively reflect on the balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
Business organizations like the CZI must be seen to be taking
a positive attitude in trading with the DRC, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
