<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Commerce Chamber Announces Boycott of Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's Chamber of
Commerce and Industry announced today its boycott of the Middle
East and North Africa Economic Conference scheduled in Doha in
November due to the lack of progress in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Chamber's Director General Ahmad Rashed Al-Haroun was
quoted by Kuwait News Agency as saying that it would officially
boycott the conference although all Kuwaiti businessmen could attend
the meeting as individuals.
</P>
<P>
The response was made by the chamber following receiving
official invitation from the Qatari Embassy in Kuwait to attend
the gathering. So far Kuwait's government still has not publicly
announced its decision as to whether to take part in the meeting
which also involves the participation of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The chamber's announcement was made three days after Saudi
Arabian Chamber of Commerce and Industry made a similar decision
of boycotting the conference by all the Saudi private businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Chamber of Commerce and Industry officially boycotted
the three previous conferences held in Casablanca, Amman and
Cairo, Kuwait News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The annual event, launched in 1994, is traditionally attended
by Arab states, Israel and their major trade partners in the
industrialized world. Nearly 1000 businessmen were attracted to
the conference last year in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Several Arab countries including Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, Syria, Lebanon, Iraq and Algeria had announced their
intention to boycott the conference in line with the Arab League
decision to suspend normalization with Israel following the
Jewish state's implementation of construction of a new Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Qatar so far has expressed several times its resolve to host
the annual economic meeting, but its Minister of State for Foreign
Affairs Ahmad Ibn Abdallah Al-Mahmud announced last month that the
conference would be downgraded from summit to the level of
foreign ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
