<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Iraq, UN to Solve Crisis Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today called on Iraq and
the United Nations to resolve through dialogue the crisis caused
by Baghdad's decision to expel American experts working with the
U.N. arms inspection team, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
An Jordanian government spokesman at a press conference urged
all parties to hold constructive dialogues to seek a solution.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also urged Iraq to implement all the U.N. Security
Council resolutions to preserve its honor and sovereignty and pave
the way for the U.N. inspection mission to carry out its task.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned against punishing Baghdad with military actions or
new economic sanctions which he said would only complicate the
situation, not helpful to produce a solution to the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided late last month to expel U.S. weapons inspectors
from Iraq and refused the entry of three U.S. inspectors Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly said it will not rule out military
option to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed economic sanctions against
Iraq after it invade Kuwait. The embargo will remain in place
until the U.N. arms inspection team certifies that Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction have all been dismantled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
