<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-01 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Vows to Ensure Transparent Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordan announced today it has
dealt with a number of election irregularities to ensure the run
for parliament smooth and transparent.
</P>
<P>
Mazen Armouti, spokesman for the Tuesday parliamentary
elections, told a press conference that legal procedures have been
taken against 11 candidates found to have confiscated illegally
the voting cards of registered voters last week.
</P>
<P>
He declined to give the names of the candidates before "legal
procedures are conclusive."
</P>
<P>
Armouti said the government will in the coming days take all
necessary measures to counter such irregularities posing threat to
the elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that 200,000 from military, security and intelligence
services registered for the elections have been dropped, for they
are barred from casting ballots by Jordan's constitution.
</P>
<P>
And some 120,000 repeated registrations have been found and
deleted from a total of 1.9 million registered eligible voters, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing to hide," said Armouti, assuring that the
government will tell the pubic anything about the election, which
will be conducted in a "transparent and honest atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian parliament is made up of the Upper and Lower
Houses. The 40 Upper House members are appointed by King
Hussein. The upcoming elections are for the lower house which has
80 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
