<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Long-term Foreign Policy Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior foreign policy
advisor has proposed that Kuwait should prepare "for a future Iraq
becoming part of the regional security order, to maintain, with GCC
and Iran, stability in the area."
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwait News Agency today, Abdullah Bshara,
advisor to Kuwait's first deputy prime minister and foreign
minister, also stressed the need to continue dialogue with Iran to
establish mutual and constructive relations.
</P>
<P>
These were outlined in a speech by Bshara to solicit a national
dialogue on Kuwait's long-term foreign policy oriented toward
maintaining regional security and cooperation with Western allies
in the years leading up to 2025.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwaiti diplomacy is to take the responsibility of restoring
the security and stability of the north Gulf state by maintaining
economic sanctions on Iraq until Baghdad complies with all the
Security Council resolutions related to its invasion of Kuwait,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is necessary to realize economic, security,
political and military integration among the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states - Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates,
Oman, Bahrain, Qatar and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need of clinching cooperation deals between
Kuwait, the European Union, the U.S. and Japan to establish a
strong alliance.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon Arab cooperation, Bshara said the old Arab
system must be replaced with a new one whose guidelines spring
from ongoing developments in the regional and international
arenas, balancing mutual interests and the economic
globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
