<HEADLINE> Iran, Kazakhstan Oppose Unilateral Move in Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Kazakhstan here today
voiced their opposition to any unilateral action by the Caspian
littoral states to exploit the resources of the sea.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, this view was
expressed at a meeting between Iranian deputy foreign minister
for Euro-American affairs, Morteza Sarmadi, and his Kazakh
counterpart Edrisov.
</P>
<P>
Sarmadi said any unilateral action on the part of the Caspian
states would further complicate the situation. He proposed that
deputy foreign ministers of the five Caspian states, which also
include Azerbaijan, Turkmenistan and Russia, hold emergency
meetings to reach a consensus in this respect.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral and multilateral consultation among the
Caspian states will not only serve to complete the legal status of
the Caspian Sea, but also boost peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sarmadi also expressed Iran's readiness to participate in
launching technical studies, exploration and exploitation of
Kazakh gas and oil and forwarding the products to the world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Edrisov said following the disintegration of former Soviet
Union, the Caspian Sea belongs to five littoral states, and
therefore all issues concerning the sea should be settled
unanimously.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea issue was raised after some of the Caspian
states signed agreements with foreign countries to explore oil
reserves in the world's biggest inland sea.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the Caspian Sea has rich oil and gas
reserves which can turn the region into another arena of
oil-producing competition and even political confrontation after
the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
In today's meeting, the Kazakh official also expressed his
country's readiness to export its goods through Iran, saying Iran
has potential in oil industry and the Iranian territory is the
shortest route for oil and gas transport from Central Asia to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
Edrisov arrived here today to exchange views on bilateral
relations with Iranian officials and to explore ways for
cooperation between the two countries in oil and gas sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
