<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Public Sector Doctors Stage Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Medical professionals of Jordan's
public hospitals and health centers started a three-day strike
today for failing to share enough revenues collected from wealthy
patients.
</P>
<P>
The strike happened in 22 public hospitals and 650 health
centers across the country, Salim Smadi, vice president of the
Jordanian Medical Association (JMA), told Xinhua this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health signed an agreement with the JMA in
1996, allowing the medical professionals in public sectors to get
60 percent of the annual fees paid by rich patients, but so far it
failed to keep its promise, said Smadi, organizer of the strike.
</P>
<P>
The professionals had only got 36 percent of the total revenues
of about 10 million U.S. dollars a year, and this was unfair for
them, said Smadi.
</P>
<P>
Under Jordan's rules, poor people and government employees are
treated free of charge in public hospitals and health centers, but
well-off patients must pay.
</P>
<P>
Public hospitals and health centers were on strikes for several
days last month. The Ministry of Health agreed on Sunday to carry
out the 1996 agreement.
</P>
<P>
But Minister of Health Ashraf Kurdi soon changed his mind and
said last night in a television interview that the 60 percent of
revenues could not be given to the professionals, and no new
negotiations with JMA would be held any more.
</P>
<P>
Kurdi said the ministry would only pay 36 percent of the
revenues because it needed to use part of the revenues for
updating equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
