<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Hashimoto Talk About Bilateral Cooperations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto today had three
round of negotiations in the frame of "no-neckties", the Russian
president's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the main goal of the meeting is to
establish good friendly relations between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky described the meeting as "successful", and in
certain issues even "more successful than we had expected," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Yeltsin-Hashimoto plan, which adopted today by the two
leaders, covers six areas and will be effective till the year of
2000.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky said this initiative includes political, economic
and financial aspects of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no guarantees of complete implementation of the
plan", he said, adding that this depends on the determination and
"ardour" of the sides.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the plan provides for cooperation in
encouraging investments, integration of Russian economy into the
world economic system, rendering assistance to Russian reform,
training of managers, strengthening of a dialogue in the energy
sector and promoting cooperation in peaceful use of nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to make joint efforts to develop the oil
and gas fields in the Russian Far East and to continue the
development of relations between the defense ministries of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the guarantees for Japanese
investments in Russia, and the two leaders decided to establish a
"hot line" between the Kremlin and the Japanese premiers'
residence in Tokyo. This will be the eighth direct telephone line
linking the Russian president with the leaders of Bonn,
Washington, London, Paris, Beijing and Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
