<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses US of Blocking Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 1st (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Trade Ministry
spokesman has accused the United states of blocking contracts Iraq
signed with foreign companies under accords with the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq News Agency (INA) today quoted the spokesman as saying
that "the U.S. has suspended 13 contracts for the first phase of
the Memorandum of Understanding signed by Iraq with the
U.N. though five months have passed and these contracts were
submitted in accordance with the Purchase and Distribution Plan
endorsed by the U.N. Secretary General."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the U.S. is still having a hostile
attitude towards the Iraqi people, making them liable to fall sick
and to starve to death.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that these contracts include purchase of
medical requisites from Russia; purchase of spare parts for farm
machinery from Holland; purchase of stand-by power generators from
France; purchase of medical requisites from England; purchase of
farm tractors and purchase of stand-by power generators from
Germany."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the contracts are designed to serve
humanitarian purposes.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman urged the Arab world and the international
community to make the U.S. change its hostile attitude towards
Iraq and get the U.N. accords with Iraq implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
