<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong To Elect Deputies To Next National People's Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
said here today the fact that Hong Kong will act as an independent
constituency for the first time and elect its own deputies to the
National People's Congress is a concrete step in implementing the
principle of "one-country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
"It also shows that Chinese citizens residing in Hong Kong have
the right to participating in managing state affairs," said the
official in charge of the general office of the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress (NPC), China's parliament.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee Saturday approved a list of deputies
for the electoral conference of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) to the Ninth NPC, which will convene
next spring in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The electoral conference was established in accordance with the
HKSAR Basic Law and an NPC resolution on electing method of HKSAR
NPC deputies, the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, Hong Kong can elect 36 deputies
and Chinese citizens among Hong Kong residents 18 and above are
eligible, but they should not represent any party or organization,
said the official.
</P>
<P>
Deputies elected should abide by Chinese Constitution and laws,
love China and love Hong Kong. They should support the principle
of "one country, two systems" and HKSAR Basic Law and perform
their duties as deputies according to NPC procedures and relevant
laws, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that deputies to the NPC from the HKSAR will be elected
in Hong Kong by Chinese citizens among the HKSAR residents.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with an election method drawn up by the NPC, the
36 deputies from the HKSAR should be elected by an electoral
conference which consists of Chinese citizens of the Selection
Committee for the first Hong Kong SAR Government, members of the
Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) who are Chinese citizens of the
HKSAR but are not concurrently members of the Election Committee,
and members of the Hong Kong SAR Provisional Legislative Council
who are Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
The electoral conference will elect an 11-member presidium to
manage the conference.
</P>
<P>
Candidates can be named jointly by 10 members or more of the
electoral conference, and the number of candidates should be
one-fifth or half more than the number of deputies to be
elected. The election must be conducted in a secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the electoral conference will hold
its first meeting this month and the election is expected to be
completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the NPC Standing Committee will preside over the
election. It will convene the electoral conference's first meeting
and supervise the election to ensure it is carried out strictly in
line with the election method approved by the NPC.
</P>
<P>
It will also publish the names of the deputies after certifying
their qualifications, the NPC official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitai Group Applies for Court Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Haitai Group, the 24th largest
conglomerate in South Korea, has sought court protection for seven
of its 15 subsidiaries to prevent bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The financially-strapped Haitai filed for court mediation for
its profitable confectionary, beverage, distribution and trading
units over the weekend in an effort to keep its managerial
rights. Meanwhile, it decided to place three unprofitable units
under court protection.
</P>
<P>
Among the remaining subsidiaries, six will be liquidated on a
step-by-step basis through mergers or sale to a third party, and
two others -- the famous pro-baseball team, Haitai Tigers, and the
Korad advertising agency -- will be managed normally.
</P>
<P>
Haitai has become the fifth business group to seek court
protection for rescheduling debt payments so far this year
following Hanbo, Jinro, Dainong, and Kia.
</P>
<P>
Reckless expansion into unrelated business areas, a sluggish
economy and bank's strict lending policies are to be blamed for
the Haitai Group's financial plight, as has been the case for
other insolvent conglomerates, financial observers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
