<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Higher Defense Council Meets on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Higher Defense
Council of Kuwait held a meeting today to discuss the latest
confrontation between Iraq and the United States and prepare to
face all possibilities arising from the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, chaired by Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime
Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah, covered the
potential outcome of the standoff and the necessity to be
prepared to face all possibilities, according to official Kuwait
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided last week to ban all U.S. inspectors taking part
in the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
eliminating weapons of mass destruction in the country following
the adoption of the U.S. and British sponsored 1134 U.N.
resolution threatening to impose new sanctions against Iraq for
hampering the task of U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. called Iraq's refusal "unacceptable" and said the
United Nations was weighing options, indicating that the options
are open to new military attacks against Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler declared that all
members of his team will go to Baghdad to resume their mandate
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation put Iraq and the U.S. again on a collision
course which caused concern from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Council of Ministers also condemned during a weekly
session today the Iraqi decision to ban U.S. members of the
inspection team from entering Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
