<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Say Acupuncture Effective Treatment for Insomnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Piercing needles into some
acupoints on the human body has proved to be effective in treating
insomnia, according to a medical report released at the Academic
Conference of the World Federation of Acupuncture-Moxibustion
Society (WFAS) here today.
</P>
<P>
After receiving acupuncture therapy, 33 percent of patients
suffering from serious-level insomnia, 56 percent of the
moderate-level and 72 percent of slight-level were able to sleep
normally, six to eight hours a night.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the acupuncture treatments, they slept less than
three, five and seven hours per day, said Dr. Jou Eel Jia, author
of the report who came from the Brazilian Institute of Holistic
Research on Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Out of 1,899 patients receiving traditional therapy, 35 percent
of the serious-level insomniacs also reported significant
improvement, he said.
</P>
<P>
"People are facing more and more life pressures now. According
to traditional Chinese medicine, excess emotional waste and
physical effort harming the heart and the spleen lead to
insomnia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Also, poor sleeping quality can be caused by emptiness of the
blood of the heart and alimentary disorder," he added.
</P>
<P>
The doctor said he pierced needles into key acupoints to
relieve uneasiness, which helped patients go to sleep more easily.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jou and his colleague, Dr. Norvan Martino Leite, also tried
combinations of acupuncture therapy with a kind of phenobarbital,
Luminal, or some herbs in a bid to treat insomnia patients, whose
symptoms could not be eased simply by acupuncture.
</P>
<P>
About 94 percent of patients have resumed sleeping six-eight
hours after receiving acupuncture-Luminal and 72 percent who
received acupuncture combined with herb therapy, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
"The situation may get worse if they just use medicines because
of drug addiction. But acupuncture therapy treats insomnia by
looking into both its root cause and symptoms," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> September 18 Incident Memorial Hall to Be Built in Shenyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A memorial hall will be
erected on the ruins of a railway section bombarded by Japanese
soldiers 66 years ago here in Shenyang of northeast China's
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The hall will commemorate the bombing which marked the
beginning of Japan's military invasion of China and other Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Liu Huaqing and other senior officials of central departments
and Liaoning province laid the foundation today for the memorial
hall.
</P>
<P>
The memorial hall, named after Sept. 18, the day of the
bombardment, should be completed by Oct. 1, 1999 when China
celebrates the 50th anniversary of its founding.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang People's Government plans to build the memorial hall
into a national monument with modern equipment and accurate
historic data.
</P>
<P>
The incident triggered China's 14-year war against fascist
aggression. From Sept. 18, 1931 until Aug. 15, 1945 when Japan
surrendered unconditionally, Japanese troops brought unprecedented
suffering to the people of Asia through their military aggression
against China and other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991 Shenyang has established several memorial buildings,
including an underground exhibition hall, near the bombardment
site. Over one million people have visited the memorial buildings.
</P>
<P>
The new hall will be an enlargement of the old memorial
buildings with displays of pictures, objects, sculptures, movies
and video films. The exhibition will consist of five parts: plot,
incident, sufferings, fighting against Japanese invasion and
victory.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang's decision to build the memorial hall has been a
popular one. People from all walks of life in Shenyang have
donated more than 20 million yuan (about 2.4 million U.S. dollars)
to build the hall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
