<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Pollution Claims Over 50,000 Lives in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 51,779 people
die prematurely every year due to air pollution in 36 Indian
cities, registering an increase of 28 percent in a period of three
to four years, a study said.
</P>
<P>
The study conducted by India's Center for Science and
Environment revealed that a World Bank report on environmental
costs in India had put the figure at 40,351 in 1992-93, according
to Press Trust of India today.
</P>
<P>
During the last three to four years, the study said, the annual
mortality caused by air pollution doubled in the cities of
Calcutta, Kanpur and Hyderabad while in Delhi the figure rose from
7,491 to 9,859, an increase of almost 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Deaths caused by air pollution in Calcutta (10,647), Delhi
(9,859), Bombay (7,023), Kanpur (3,639) and Ahmedabad (3,006)
along with other major cities account for 66 percent of the total
premature deaths in India in 1995-96, the study added.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the number of illness that require hospitalization
or medical treatment because of air pollution, the figure is
currently 26 million a year, the study said.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, the levels of disease-causing suspended
particulate matter in Delhi, Kanpur, Bombay and Calcutta, among
others, are three to five times higher than the acceptable limit
set by the World Health Organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
