<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hatanaka Sets World Record in Wheelchair Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Kazu Hatanaka of Japan won the
women's wheelchair marathon Sunday with a new world record
clocking of 1:39.41 while Switzerland's Heinz Frei captured the
men's title for the fifth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old Hatanaka sped her wheelchair the full 42.195
kilometers (26.16 miles) in the Oita International Wheelchair
Marathon, breaking the record of 1:42:00 set by Dane Connier
Hansen in Switzerland in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Monica Wetterstrom of Sweden was second in 1:39.41 and Luise
Sauvage of Australia was third in 1:46.58.
</P>
<P>
In the men's category, Frei won the marathon in 1:24:49,
beating Saul Mendoza of Mexico by three minutes, 19 seconds.
</P>
<P>
It was the 39-year-old Frei's fifth victory in a row and
seventh overall in the yearly race.
</P>
<P>
Kazuya Murozuka of Japan was third in 1:31:35, followed by Ben
Lucas of New Zealand in 1:31.35, Jun Hiromichi of Japan in 1:32:25.
</P>
<P>
Aaron Gordian of Mexico captured the half-marathon, covering
the 21.0975 kilometers (13.08 miles) in the meet record of 45
minutes, 57 seconds, beating his compatriot Jorgeluna Zepeda by
one second.
</P>
<P>
Fidel Aguilar of Mexico was third in 45:59.
</P>
<P>
Kyoko Okuyama of Japan took the women's half-marathon in 54.40,
followed by Ariadne Hernandez of Mexico in 57.38 and Gunilla
Wallengren of Sweden in 1:01:19.
</P>
<P>
A total of 100 men and women from 27 countries plus 333
Japanese competed in the even for disabled persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
