<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Not to Enter European Exchange Rate System: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 2 (Xinhua) -- British Chancellor of Exchequer
Gordon Brown said here today that Britain does not want to
re-enter the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM), but he set
the tone for British participation in the European single currency
in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the current debate about whether Britain should
return to the ERM before joining a single currency, which is to be
launched in 1999, Brown said: "We have no intention of entering
the ERM."
</P>
<P>
"Every country wants a stable exchange rate," Brown said in an
interview with BBC Television. He said that he wanted to have a
strong and competitive pound over the medium term.
</P>
<P>
However, Brown said that there is a strong business consensus
for entry into a European single currency as some 60 percent of
Britain's trade was within Europe.
</P>
<P>
But he said he was not ready to abandon the pound during the
present Labor term, which expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
A standing committee on preparations for the European Economic
and Monetary Union would advise business on "problems of
transition" before a decision on entry was made, he said.
</P>
<P>
The last Conservative government left the ERM in disarray in
September 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
