<HEADLINE> Unemployment Runs High in Vietnamese Countryside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 2 (Xinhua) --- A labor surplus continues to put
heavy pressure on Vietnam's job market, particularly in the
countryside, where 80 percent of the country's population live,
local press reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said although 1 million jobs are created each year
in Vietnam, unemployment and under-employment remain serious in
its rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Labour, War Invalids and Social Affairs
said 40 percent of the 25 million people in the Red river and
Mekong river deltas are fully or partly out of job.
</P>
<P>
What's more worrisome is the low education and professional
level of farmers. Although 93.43 percent of them are literate and
40 percent have completed junior high school, only 7 percent have
had job training, four times lower than in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has adopted a series of policies to
encourage farmers to provide their children with higher or
vocational education. But the percentage of young rural people who
had received higher education or job training remains very low,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
