<HEADLINE> FIS Apologises to Japanese Olympic Organiser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Ski Federation
(FIS) head apologised for calling the Japanese chief organiser of
the 1998 Winter Olympics as a dictator here on Sunday at a news
conference in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
"Towards Mr. Kobayashi, I present all my excuses and apologies,
Marc Hodler said. Hodler was quoted as saying in an interview with
the Sankei newspaper on Sunday that Kobayashi was a "new dictator"
after Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
The NAOC and the FIS broke into quarrel four years ago on
whether to raise the length of the downhill course from 1,680
meters to 1,800 meters.
</P>
<P>
Kobayashi, the director general of the NAOC, resists strongly
to an FIS demand to lengthen the course, which would take into a
nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
IOC, FIS and NAOC officials agreed to leave the issue to a
select panel which will include Kobayashi, Yoshiaki Tsutumi,
honarary president of the Japanese Olympic Committee and other
sports leaders.
</P>
<P>
The NAOC executive board will decide on November 20 on whether
on raise the starting gate of the premier siiing event to prevent
it becoming the shortest downhill course in Olympic history.
</P>
</TEXT>
