<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dane, Chinese, South Koreans Win at HK Open Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- World number one Peter Gade
Christensen revenged his two previous losses to compatriot and world
number nine Thomas Stuer-Lauridsen by beating him to take the men's
singles title at the 170,000 U.S. dollars Millennium Hong Kong Open
Badminton Championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a match between two of China's new stars, Gong Ruina
defeated Wu Huimin 2-1 in the women's singles final today. Both
were unseeded layers here.
</P>
<P>
But it was the South Koreans who bagged most titles, in the
men's and women's doubles and mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
Quick-footed Christensen, the second seed for the five-star event,
took over the world's top position from teammate Poul-Erik
Hoyer-Larsen earlier this week. But he had lost to Stuer-Lauridsen
twice in their only two previous meetings.
</P>
<P>
Christensen, finalist in his four latest events including the
Danish Open two weeks ago where he lost to China's Dong Jiong,
overcame a one-game deficit in the final today to beat fourth-seeded
Stuer-Lauridsen 7-15, 15-6, 15-4.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to beat Thomas (Stuer-Lauridsen) as he had being
playing very well these days," said Christensen, 20.
</P>
<P>
He addmitted that his opponent had controlled the net in the
opening game. "But I tried to build myself up and did quite well,
especially in the third game," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I did a defensive game in the early stage today. I didn't
expect him to be so aggressive, which he was in the first game,"
Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old winner said he "had very good legs during the second
and third games" and was not tired at all after the match.
</P>
<P>
"So long as my legs are good enough, I think I can play for at
least 10 years," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Christensen analysed that his opponent's failure was probably due
to his compartively easier draw so he had not played many hard matches
so far to reach his shape.
</P>
<P>
China's Gong Ruina won the opening game 11-8 in the women's singles
final, with her usual tricky and consistent game. Her teammate Wu
Huimin won one game back in the second by taking three points in a row
after they tied 8-8, largely due to unforced errors from Gong.
</P>
<P>
But more experienced Gong came back strongly in the decisive third
game where she led all the way through to her triumph after an early
2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Kim Dong-Moon and Ha Tae Kwon took an upper hand over
Indonesia's third seeds Hermono and Hiao Eng in the men's doubles
final and won the match 15-4, 15-12.
</P>
<P>
The women's doubles title went to South Korea's fifth seeds Chung
Jae Hee and Ra Kyung Min, who downed China's top-seeded Liu Lu and
Qian Hong 15-7, 15-12.
</P>
<P>
In an all-South Koreans mixed doubles final, top-seeds Kim Dong
Moon and Ra Kyung Min won over fifth-seeded Ha Tae Kwon and Chung Jae
Hee 15-12, 15-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
