SHENYANG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Overseas funds are playing an
increasingly bigger role in upgrading state-owned enterprises in
Shenyang, a heavy industrial base in China, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
In the last four years, the share of overseas funding in the
city's state-owned enterprises invested in technology has
increased by 20 percent each year. Overseas funds are expected to
rise to account for 60 percent of the total technology investment
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The use of overseas funds to upgrade technology is important in
reforming state-owned enterprises, Shenyang Mayor Mu Suixin said.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1996, 1.1 billion U.S. dollars was committed to
Shenyang's industrial enterprises by overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Mu said these enterprises should try to learn from new
technology and advanced managerial expertise from their overseas
partners.
</P>
<P>
Joint ventures with Toshiba Elevator Co. and Toyota Motor Co.,
for instance, have benefited from their Japanese partners'
managerial skills which focus on tapping the potential of staff
members and reducing costs.
</P>
<P>
Of Shenyang's 340 large and medium state-owned enterprises in
such industries as machinery, metallurgical, automotive and
textile, more than 50 rank first in their industries in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
