<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Supports Bi-Communal Business Contacts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations fully
backs the Cypriot bi-communal business contacts as a way to
promote rapprochement between the two sides on the island, a top
U.N. envoy on Cyprus has said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. resident representative for Cyprus Gustave Feissel said
in an interview with the English-language daily Cyprus Mail
published today that he thought business was a very important
area in which concrete steps could be taken to help reach a
comprehensive Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
"These kinds of efforts should be encouraged," Feissel said,
pointing out that it would not be conducive to progress in the
protracted Cyprus problem to wait until after a solution before
beginning such contacts.
</P>
<P>
Feissel said that not enough had been done to promote
rapprochement between the two sides, adding the U.N. always felt
much more is needed to be done to send the right messages.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash that they support joint
business meetings, the U.N. official said it was not enough to
express good intentions, but do things.
</P>
<P>
"Things must go from words to deeds. The authorities must
send a clear message that contacts are good," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus
(UNFICYP) would facilitate further meetings between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots at the U.N.-controlled Ledra Palace Hotel in
the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Greek and Turkish Cypriot businessmen along with their
counterparts from Greece and Turkey held business meetings in
Istanbul, Turkey, and in Athens, Greece, over the last few
months to promote rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkey landed its troops in Cyprus and took over 37 percent
of the island in the wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was only recognized by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have still been trying to
reunite the divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal federation
despite no tangible results have been achieved in the bicommunal
peace talks for the past 23 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
