<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Urges Education to Combat Drug Abuse Among Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese public
security official has called for more education of young people to
combat a serious drug problem.
</P>
<P>
Bai Jingfu, vice minister of Public Security, said in a recent
interview that large-scale educational campaigns need to be
launched among young people and that the program should begin with
students in primary and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
Bai, who is also deputy director of China's National Narcotics
Control Commission, said China has 520,000 drug addicts, 80
percent of whom are young people and teenagers.
</P>
<P>
"Having opened China as an international drug-trafficking route
since the 1980s, some drug-smuggling rings are now developing
China as a drug consumption market by luring young people into the
habit," Bai said.
</P>
<P>
Teenagers are curious and have little social experience, he
said, which makes them the most vulnerable. Bai added that "some
of them are just seeking stimulation or trying to be trendy."
</P>
<P>
He warned of the dangers of drugs and the difficulty of
shaking the habit. He said most addicts are remorseful and many of
them have had their future ruined.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important to start telling young people, especially
school students, of the dangers of drug addiction," Bai
said. "Drug education should be a required course in school."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
