<HEADLINE> Arab League's Chief Denounces Israeli Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
22-member Arab League Ahmad Esmat Abdul-Meguid denounced Israel
for its hardline stand in the Middle East peace process here today.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said that Israel's current policies and activities are
not "capable of promoting the peace process," instead, its
obstinacy in its ideas and religion will "put the region to the
edge of a danger gap."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his opening speech at a United Arab
Emirates (UAE)-organized three-day symposium which opened here
today under the title "the future of Arab states and the role of
the Arab League."
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel's current policies are based on "taking
everything" instead of "giving anything," and such a stand has
opened the door for violence and deteriorated the situation in the
Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Meguid called on the international community, particularly the
two Mideast peace co-sponsors of the United States and Russia, to
take measures against the Israeli policies of "the expansion of
Jewish settlement in Arab lands and the violation of Arab rights."
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process was stalled after Israel began
the construction of a Jewish settlement in March in Arab East
Jerusalem which the Palestinians want to be the capital of their
future state.
</P>
<P>
Despite world criticism, Israel refused to stop the
implementation of the settlement plan, which has caused violent
disputes between Israel and Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
