<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Install Computerized Mapping System for  Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Tourists to Hong Kong can
literally have at their fingertips the latest information on
hotels, restaurants, shopping and scenic spots in town when a
computerized map inquiry system is in place early next year.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Lands Department of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China said today that the system
would integrate advanced Internet map technology to provide a
high-technology tourism facility in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"A number of display kiosks will be installed at popular
tourist locations such as Mass Transit Railway stations and the
airport," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Inside the kiosk will be a computer terminal. Through a digital
location map on the screen, a tourist can gain access to a wealth
of information including sightseeing, shopping, hotel and dining
services, he said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the traditional maps, the system will also furnish an
inquirer with interesting photographs and videos relating to the
selected places or events.
</P>
<P>
A useful feature is the link-up with the WonderNet Website of
the Hong Kong Tourist Association from which hotel room rates and
facilities can be retrieved and reservation made, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The map will also be able to perform some intelligent
geographical search of special facilities such as post offices,
police stations, and shopping places within a five-minute's walk
from where the tourist is. A convenient traveling route to the
destination will also be suggested.
</P>
<P>
The tourist information will be available to all Internet users
worldwide. This will certainly be of interest to prospective
tourists and help them plan their sightseeing routes before
arriving in Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
While the system is targeted primarily at tourists, it will
also be available for use by the general public and the access to
the system is free, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Funded by the Hong Kong Jockey Club Charities Trust, the system
will be set up by the Survey and Mapping Office (SMO) of the Lands
Department with the assistance of the Hong Kong Tourist
Association.
</P>
<P>
The SMO will regularly update the data bank to take account of
the rapid changing relief and topography of land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
