<HEADLINE> India's Inflation Falls Below 4 Percent Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- India's annual rate of
inflation fell below the four percent mark to 3.97 percent for the
week ended October 18 despite an increase in railway freight
charges during the week, Press Trust of India said today.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, inflation in the previous week was 4.13 percent
and that in the corresponding week last year 6.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fall in inflation is mainly due to a decline in the primary
food articles, which eased by 0.5 percent during the week under
review.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the wholesale price index (WPI) for "all
commodities" (base 1981-82=100) fell by 0.1 percent to 329.8
during the week from 330.1 in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Economists here have suggested that the low level of inflation
may be due to slackening of demand in the economy, which is quite
evident from the slow movement in the prices of "manufactured
products" in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
