<HEADLINE> Weekly Review on Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The worst-ever stock crash in
major world markets last Tuesday has also affected speculatives on
the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) which suffered a sharp setback
pushing the sensitive index down by over 154 points during this
week.
</P>
<P>
The BSE had only two sessions this week due to celebrations of
an Indian national festival.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index showed a sharp fall of 154.22 points to
close the week at 3,803.24 from the last weekend close of
3,957.46.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-100 index also lost substantially by 59.27 points to
end the week at 1,644.16 as against the previous weekend close of
1,703.43.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the Dollex were quoted sharply down at 371.39
and 170.53 at the weekend compared with the last weekend close of
382.03 and 175.41 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The volume of business during the two-session week was 7.7522
billion rupees (about 215.34 million US dollars) as against
46.7853 billion rupees (about 1.2996 billion dollars) in the last
week.  
</P>
