<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New US Bill Worries Indian Software Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indian software industry
has expressed serious concern over a bill in the US Congress
which, if enacted, would affect the country's software exports to
the United States, Press Trust of India said today.
</P>
<P>
The bill, seeking to amend the immigration and nationality act
of the US, would increase the financial and administrative costs
of hiring Indian software professionals, according to India's
National Association of Software and Service Companies (NASSCOM).
</P>
<P>
"The United States is the biggest market for Indian software
exports. The increased burden placed on a US company when hiring
an Indian professional would hamper the free flow of software
trade between India and the US," NASSCOM Executive Director Dewang
Mehta said.
</P>
<P>
In the event of the proposed bill being made into law, the
projected software export of one billion dollars to the United
States is expected to be hit sharply, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The bill is discriminatory in nature. India's competitive
advantage in software would be stifled by these kind of non-tariff
barriers being put up by developed countries," Mehta asserted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
