<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moves for New Sanction on Nigeria Defeated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria escaped from fresh
sanctions, including visa restrictions and an oil embargo, at the
just-concluded 25th session of the Lome Convention's joint
assembly in Togo.
</P>
<P>
A resolution on it fell through when the European Union (EU)
and member countries of the African, Caribbean and Pacific
Association (ACP) could not reach an agreement on the proposed
measures, the Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by the Nigerian delegation to the
meeting, 35 EU member countries voted against the resolution
introduced by a British parliamentarian, while three voted for it
with two abstentions.
</P>
<P>
On the ACP side, the statement added, 21 countries voted
against the resolution while 15 voted for it with two
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The rules of the joint assembly provide that both sides must
agree on any motion or resolution before it is adopted.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the two groups voted separately on the
resolution after an agreement to adopt a proposal for a secret
ballot proposed by the EU members.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, the statement explained, would have imposed
visa restrictions on Nigerian government officials and oil
embargo, frozen the assets of government officials and their
families, and ensured the re-allocation of uncommitted resources,
frozen two years ago, meant for the country to other ACP members.
</P>
<P>
It would also have provided for the publication, by EU member
states, of the list of arms export to Nigeria as well as
jeopardized the chances of participation of the country's
national football team -- the Super Eagle, in the France World
Cup by denying the players visas.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been under sanctions including visa restrictions
on government officials and arms embargo imposed by EU member
countries and other countries including the United States and
Canada due to alleged human rights abuse.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth last Monday decided to extend the two-year
suspension of Nigeria's membership due to an end this month for
another year, as a means to put pressure on the country's
transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
The hostility of its traditional friends in the West has
forced Nigeria to turn to the East for new friends.
</P>
<P>
Rapid development has been witnessed in recent years in the
relations between Nigeria and some Asian countries, including
Malaysia, China and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
