<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Apply Interactive Multimedia on Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's scientists and
educators are making joint efforts to promote the application of
information technology on teaching and learning in secondary and
primary schools.
</P>
<P>
With the advancement of technologies and the increasing amount
of information, the use of interactive multimedia would help
maximize learning opportunities, experts in the telecommunications
sector and local educators agreed at a seminar on the impact of
interactive multimedia on teaching and learning held on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by Hong Kong Telecom IMS, the largest
Internet Service Provider in Hong Kong, and Chinese Books
CyberStore, a book store which can be accessed through Internet.
</P>
<P>
"Interactive multimedia, such as the Internet, CD-ROMs and
Interactive TV (ITV), represent major pioneering technologies in
information technology development, and they are capable of
providing extensive resources for a diversity of educational
purposes," said Gabriel Yu, chairman of Chinese Books CyberStore.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Telecom IMS Managing Director William Lo said the
coming century represents a new world of information and
technology and It is imperative to provide youngsters with the
best possible information technology education to meet the
challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Books CyberStore will open an interactive book
store later this month, through which parents and children can
browse books with ease and pleasure at home by categories of
subjects and ages.
</P>
<P>
The Rainbow Land Interactive Book Store is a typical example of
the creative use of interactive multimedia technology in making
teaching and learning a more interesting and fruitful experience
for teachers, parents and children, in schools and at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
