<HEADLINE> International Blood Transfusion Conference Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The 8th Asia-Pacific Regional
Congress of the International Society of Blood Transfusion closed
here today.
</P>
<P>
Attending were more than 600 experts from China, the United
States, Japan, Britain, the Netherlands and 21 other
countries. The conference was sponsored by the Chinese Society of
Blood Transfusion, the International Health Exchange Center under
the Ministry of Health and the Beijing Red Cross Blood Center.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference, the first of its kind in China,
focused on 15 topics, including a national plan of blood
transfusion, related diseases, clinical uses and blood products.
</P>
<P>
The conference attracted more than 200 experts from the
Asia-Pacific region, America and Europe, and more than 300 papers
were presented. Equipment and instruments in blood transfusions
also were on exhibit during the conference.
</P>
<P>
China has made progress in recent years in improving the blood
transfusion system, adding more than 340 blood stations and 15,000
blood banks across the country, said Cai Shengga, president of the
the Chinese Society of Blood Transfusion.
</P>
<P>
Cai said the blood transfusion system in China is shifting from
paid contributions to free donations. The blood donation
regulations, approved by the standing committees of the local
people's congress, have already been implemented in 22 cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Takes Measures Against Drugs Menace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard
today launched his government's response to the drugs menace -- a
three-year campaign aimed at halting the tide of narcotics
flooding the country.
</P>
<P>
The 87.5 million Australian dollar (61 million US dollar)
campaign is also aimed at funding education, research and the
reintegration of drug users into the community.
</P>
<P>
"My government wants to prevent a new generation of drug users
and addicts in Australia," Howard told a Sydney press conference
early today, Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The three-year campaign, which Howard stressed was just the
start, will tackle drugs on three fronts. The main thrust will be
an assault on the multi-billion dollar drug trade.
</P>
<P>
With figures showing 634 Australians died last year from
heroin-related deaths and 300,000 more were using the drug, Howard
was keen to point out the strategy intended to achieve a balance
between tackling importers and distributors and dealing with
problems on the street.
</P>
<P>
Improved drug education in schools, treatment for users and
funding for new research were included in the package.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he wanted to work in partnership with the states
and territories, no matter what differences they had on other
issues, and "with parents, teachers, volunteers and community
organizations and health workers to develop a plan to take us into
the next century".  
</P>
</TEXT>
