<HEADLINE> UN Urged to Send Neutral Experts to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian dailies today urged
the United Nations not to be the instrument of the United States
and to send neutral experts to inspect the Iraqi arms
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Iran News said that "Baghdad
claims that 10 Americans and a 40-member inspection team are
busy gathering intelligence in Iraq, and due to the orientation
of the American administration we cannot disregard the Iraqi
allegations."
</P>
<P>
The daily said that all nations must fully support the
U.N. Security Council's efforts and call for destruction of
long-range missiles and nuclear, biological, and chemical
weapons, not only in Iraq, but also across the globe.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the inspection in Iraq, the 10 Americans can easily
be replaced by experts from neutral countries so that neither
Iraq nor the U.S. can use this issue as an excuse to fan flames
of another crisis, it said.
</P>
<P>
Another daily The English-language Tehran Times said that it
is the credibility of the U.N. which is at stake and it should
not become an instrument in the hands of the U.S. for achieving
its objectives.
</P>
<P>
With the Middle East peace process in virtual deadlock, the
U.S., as the main sponsor of the process, is trying to buy time
as a face-saving device to restore its credibility as the
mediator, the paper said in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
It is for this reason that the U.S. is trying to shift the
center of the crisis from Tel Aviv to Baghdad for sometime to
find a solution for the deadlock, it said.
</P>
<P>
These developments, coupled with the disappointment of Arab
countries with the outcome of the peace process, have created a
new atmosphere in the region, undermining U.S. status as the real
protector of regional security, the editorial noted.
</P>
<P>
It said that although Iran supports implementation of the
U.N. resolutions on Iraq, both the U.S. and U.N. must give up
their double standard approaches and policies as they threaten
international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
If U.N. resolutions are to be implemented, it should apply to
all U.N. resolutions and not just to those on Iraq alone, the
paper added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has announced that it would bar Americans from serving
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), which is inspecting mass
destructive weapons programs of Iraq. The decision caused a new
round of confrontation between Iraq and Western countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
