<HEADLINE> Meeting with Hashimoto Breakthrough, Says Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today described his informal meeting with Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto in Krasnoyarsk as "a real breakthrough" in
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said at a joint news conference after the summit that a
Yeltsin-Hashimoto plan was the main outcome of today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The plan envisages the strengthening of cooperation between the
two countries and comprises a number of points which provide a
real basis for partnership, the Itar-Tass news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto described the meeting as an excellent start into the
next century, the agency said in a dispatch from Krasnoyarsk, a
Far East city of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders agreed to do their best to conclude a peace treaty
between Russia and Japan by the year 2000, based on the October
1993 Tokyo declaration.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Yeltsin during the meeting that Tokyo was
accepting Moscow's proposal to insure trade deals with Russia
against the guarantees of private Russian Banks and to lower the
insurance premiums for trade transactions with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russian Vice-Premier Boris Nemtsov was cited as saying that the
Japanese Prime Minister personally came out with such an
initiative for the first time in the history of the
Russian-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Both Yeltsin and Hashimoto had left Krasnoyarsk after the
two-day meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
