<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New System Enforcing Traffic Law Developed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli company has
developed a new effective computerized system that can help
police catch violators of traffic laws, the Jerusalem Post daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Telem system, developed by Tracon Systems, is based on
metal sensor tracks laid across a road and attached to a computer
and video camera.
</P>
<P>
The new system is different from existing computerized
law-enforcement systems based on electronmagnetic radiation. The
Technion said the new system can detect the speed and
acceleration rate of vehicles passing between bands of metal.
</P>
<P>
Telem can also detect a vehicle's passing over a solid white
line into oncoming traffic, a frequent cause of accidents, failing
to stop at a red light, a stop sign or crosswalks, and driving on
the road shoulder.
</P>
<P>
A digital camera automatically records the number of the
vehicle that has violated the law and transmits the data to the
police's central computer, human hands are not involved in the
process.
</P>
<P>
Within 10 minutes, a printed report and bill for the fine is
sent to the violator's address. Tracon Systems said Telem
operates day or night, in any type of weather. And the price is
relatively low compared to other road surveillance systems and
requires only minimal maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Due to its simplicity, exactness, low cost and automatic
enforcement of a large number of violations, Israeli police has
expressed interest in applying the new systems on the country's
main roads in order to check the increasing problems of car
accidents, that have cost more 500 lives so far this year in the
country with a population of only 57 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
