<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flamingo Population Reduced in Kenya's Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The flamingo population has
failed to build up to more than half a million in Lake Nakuru of
Kenya for the past several years, the Sunday Nation today quoted
conservationists as saying.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the famous lesser flamingo lingered below
50,000 by the beginning of the year and had not built beyond
300,000 even after the heavy rains in May and June.
</P>
<P>
Lake Nakuru, about 160 kilometers northwest of Nairobi, used
to host 1.5 million flamingoes, more than half of the lesser
flamingo population in the entire east African region.
</P>
<P>
Flamingoes have turned the Lake Nakuru National Park one of
the leading tourist attractions in the east African country which
receives about 200,000 local and foreign tourists annually.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in the number of flamingoes is described as a
symptom of a deep-seated ecological crisis unfolding in the lake
area, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The lake has markedly lowered volume of water than ever
recorded in the last eight years and had witnessed severe water
recession during the dry seasons in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The water recession had resulted in disrupting the complex
food chain of biomass and diversity of species in the lake
established over a long period.
</P>
<P>
According to conservationists, most affected have been the
lower animals and plants like algae, molluses, cruslacea and
insect larvae which serve as food for massive flamingoes in the
lake.
</P>
<P>
For example, conservationists said, the chironomous fly larvae
and tilapia grahami fishes which used to exist in millions have
disappeared from Lake Nakuru yet the fly served as a critical
food resources to many birds and invertebrate animals.
</P>
<P>
Conservationists suspect that the newly-built Nakuru Sewerage
Rehabilitation Project could have contributed very significantly
to the reduction of nutrient loads flowing into the lake, leading
to low primary productivity and subsequently weak food chain.
</P>
<P>
But they pointed out that the real danger for the lake's
survival was now being posed by the massive destruction of
forests in critical water catchment areas where more than 20,000
families have been settled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Impact of Southeast Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Four months ago, when the Thai
financial crisis swiftly spread to the rest of Southeast Asia, it
caught almost everybody by surprise.
</P>
<P>
Four months later, when the spill-over effect of the fallout
reached beyond Southeast Asia, it, again, nearly caught everybody
off guard.
</P>
<P>
As the crisis entered its fifth month, Southeast Asian
currencies have already depreciated between 10 percent and over 35
percent, the regional economic growth has slowed own, and price
hikes, lay-offs, bankruptcies have often hit headlines of national
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, stock markets in other parts of Asia, and in the
pacific, Western Europe and America have experienced ups and downs
in recent weeks because of the negative effects of Southeast
Asia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
How great is the impact of the crisis on the regional and the
world economy? No body seems to be able to answer the question
with assurance at the present stage of the crisis, and no body
knows for sure when the crisis will be over.
</P>
<P>
Only one thing is certain: the extent of the impact has
confounded most businessmen, investors and economists.
</P>
<P>
In Southeast Asia, the four-month old crisis has created a
great deal of political and economic uncertainties. Demonstrations
and protests against price increases, lay-offs and falling living
standards have triggered political instability in some countries.
</P>
<P>
Due to the unexpected extent of the damage to the region,
economists hesitate to predict whether the economies of Thailand,
The Philippines, Indonesia and Malaysia would pick up in the
short-term or in the medium-term.
</P>
<P>
According to Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, the
recent turmoil in his country's financial markets has set back by
10 years his efforts to turn the nation into a developed country
by 2020.
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath of the crisis, Asian Development Bank
economists estimated recently that the real gross domestic product
(GDP) growth in the region will decelerate further from 7.4 in
1996 to between 4.9 percent and 5.7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The forecast growth rate range for 1998 is between 4 percent
and 5.5 percent, and for 1999 it is between 5.2 percent and 6.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
If the estimates are to be proved correct, the growth rates
would be the lowest for the region in a decade.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, the economy could only expand between 1.6 percent
and 1.9 percent this year, and 2 percent to 2.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the crisis, inflation in the region is projected
to rise from 6.6 percent in 1996 to 9 percent this year. Next
year's inflation rate is likely to rise by 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economic slowdown in Southeast Asia has cut down the
average growth rate for developing Asian economies from 7.5
percent in 1996 to a range of 6.1 percent to 7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate for the Asian economy in 1998 has been forecast
between 5.3 percent and 6.2 percent, also the lowest in a decade.
</P>
<P>
In addition to developing Asian economies, the worst hit
country will probably be Japan, whose bank lending to Southeast
Asia accounts for about 60 percent of foreign lendings to the
region. The Japanese banks' lending exposure to Thailand alone is
almost 40 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis will make Southeast Asian banks more
difficult to repay their debts, as they too are suffering from
mounting non-performing loans, which will peak at 73 billion
dollars in Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia, and
Singapore Through 1998.
</P>
<P>
Because of the inter-linking of the global economy, the
Southeast Asian crisis could hamper economic growth in other parts
of the world. While only 7 percent of European Union exports go
directly to Asia, European firms have been pushing hard for a
bigger share of the fast-growing markets in recent years, but
their efforts have been clearly hampered by the slowdown in
several Asian economies caused by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
German carmaker BMW has seen sales in Thailand tumbled 47
percent in the first nine months of this year and is now facing a
sharp increase in import duties in Malaysia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The sharp devaluation of Southeast Asian currencies will make
their goods cheaper abroad, and European companies will have to
cut their prices to cope with cheaper Asian products.
</P>
<P>
U.S. companies will also be affected because some 15 percent of
their exports go to Asia, economists said.
</P>
<P>
French experts warned that an Asian-wide crisis could wipe 0.1
to 0.2 percentage points off French GDP.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, as the crisis is continuing in Southeast Asia,
its full impact on the regional and world economy is still
unpredictable, economists said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
