<HEADLINE> Zambian Attorney General Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Attorney General George
Chilupe resigned on Saturday and President Frederick Chiluba
accepted the resignation, Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
State House spokesman Richard Sakala confirmed the resignation
but declined to comment on it.
</P>
<P>
But sources told the local newspaper that it was the president
who asked the attorney general to resign after some "legal
problems were noticed in the privatization of the Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM)."
</P>
<P>
A total of nine units are to be privatized under the ZCCM and
so far four units have been sold. Kansanshi mine was sold on
competitive tender basis to Cyprus Amax of the United States for
28 million U.S. dollars. The sale raised concern when some miners
lamented that it was undervalued.
</P>
<P>
Chilupe, who participated in the privatization of a number of
companies, is said to have been summoned by Chiluba to explain a
number of issues and was later told to resign, according to the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Chilupe was appointed attorney general on July 23, 1995 to take
over from Ali Hamir after the latter's contract expired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
