<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Lankan Air Force to Recruit Women to Fly 0ver  War-zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Air Force
(SLAF), desperate to fill vacancies left by the loss of dozens of
pilots in plane crashes, has begun a drive to recruit women and
train them to fly over war-zones, military sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Advertisements were put on this week's Daily News, an English
newspaper with the largest circulation in the island nation, with
the headline: "Lady pilots, there is a place in the sky for women
too."
</P>
<P>
Air Force Chief Air Marshal Oliver Ranasinghe was quoted by
local press reports as saying the SLAF needs to recruit at least
100 more pilots by January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the SLAF has tried its utmost in the last six
months to recruit men to fill the vacancies, loading government
and independent newspapers, in both Sinhala and English, with
color ads, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, the SLAF has decided to recruit
women.
</P>
<P>
The sources said those recruited will first be posted in
surveillance and transport planes, as flight engineers, and then
co-pilots.
</P>
<P>
It will be at least two years before they will be able to take
command of aircraft as pilots, and only then they may be allowed
to pilot Israeli Kfir jets or Ukranian Mi-24 attack helicopters,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The SLAF has lost 19 planes and helicopters, including four
warplanes and attack helicopters, in the past two and a half
years.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the SLAF has employed women only in ground roles,
mainly for office work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
