<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Continues Boycotting Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The seventh session of the
Bangladeshi Parliament is set to begin this afternoon in the
absence of lawmakers from the main opposition party, as all moves
to break the current stand-off failed.
</P>
<P>
The latest initiative of Speaker Rashid Chowdhury also failed
on Saturday as the opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)
leaders turned down his invitation to attend a luncheon meeting
with the ruling party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the BNP representatives refused to attend a meeting
of the Business Advisory Committee of the House on Saturday,
Parliament Secretariat sources said. The meeting was attended by
the ruling Awami (people's) League and other opposition parties --
Jatiya (national) Party and Jamaat-e-Islami.
</P>
<P>
The BNP lawmakers started boycott of parliament from its last
autumn session on August 30 and made their return to the House
conditional to fulfillment of their demands for proportional
representation on parliamentary committees and an end to what they
said government repression on the BNP party leaders and workers.
</P>
<P>
The government, while agreeing to discuss the issues inside the
House, announced that the parliamentary committees would be formed
soon even in the absence of BNP members as the House would remain
ineffective without the parliamentary committees.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the present session is expected to deal
with some burning issues like a peace accord on the
insurgency-torn Chittagong Hill Tracts, which was billed by the
BNP as "betraying the country's independence and sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
But the session would become more irrelevant if the BNP
lawmakers remain outside the parliament chamber.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Exports Uncompetitive Against S.E. Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Indian exporters are being
rendered uncompetitive against rivals from Thailand, Malaysia,
Singapore and Indonesia due to the recent devaluation of the
currencies of these Southeast Asian countries, the local press
said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent study by the Indian Institute of Foreign
Trade, India stands to lose on account of devaluation of the Thai
baht since the export basket of both countries are similar.
</P>
<P>
But India need not bother about devaluation of the Philippines
peso as the export structures of the two countries are highly
dissimilar, the study said.
</P>
<P>
India's exports would become less competitive by about 15
percent than Thai and Indonesian exports, 10 percent against
Malaysia and the Philippines, and only three percent against
Singapore, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
After a detailed analysis of the depreciation of the currencies
of Southeast Asian countries against the U.S. dollar, the study
has concluded that India would be worst affected in the case of
food products and manufactured goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
