<HEADLINE> Turkish, Greek PMs to Meet Amid Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish and Greek prime
ministers are expected to meet amid simmering tensions between the
two countries, while attending a summit of the southeastern
European countries in Greece next week.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz will meet his Greek
counterpart Costas Simitis at the two-day summit of Balkan leaders
scheduled to start on the Greek island of Crete Monday, Turkish
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem and State Ministers Rifat
Serdaroglu and Cavit Kavak will accompany Yilmaz during his visit
to Crete.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from Bulgaria, Romania, Albania, Yugoslavia and
Macedonia will attend the summit sponsored by Greece to discuss
regional economic cooperation, security and stability, good
neighborhood relations, relations with European Union and North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), the role of the Balkans on
the international forum and the expansion of European institutions.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Turkey and Greece have been worsening
since the Cypriot government announced that it will not give up
the controversial plan to buy 150 kilometer-range anti-aircraft
S-300 missiles from Russia. Meanwhile, Greece accused Turkey of
numerous violations of its air space.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has threatened to take steps to ensure Cyprus not to
deploy the S-300 missiles, while Athens pledged to help Cyprus if
it is militarily attacked.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both NATO members, station troops in Cyprus,
which has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since when Turkish troops invaded
and took the northern third of the island in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
