<HEADLINE> Final Bidding for Seven Major Projects End in S. Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Final Bidding for seven major
construction projects in South Sri Lanka has ended, a spokeswoman
for the Southern Development Authority (SDA) said today.
</P>
<P>
She said a technical evaluation committee will be called in
soon and companies which are bidding for the projects will make
their presentations by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The projects include an international sea port at Hambantota,
an oil refinery near the port, an international airport 18 km
north of the port, diversions of the Uma Oya River and the Menik
Ganga River, a power plant, a highway and an electrified railway.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the projects is estimated to cost two
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A total of 84 companies participated in the bidding but only
seven of them entered the last round of bidding on Friday, the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
She said each of the seven companies is bidding for more than
one projects.
</P>
<P>
The Hambantota sea port project attracted more than half of the
bidders, she said.
</P>
<P>
Hambantota is considered to be an ideal location for a port
because it offers the least deviation on the main sea line,
shipping experts said. It also has a natural deep water basin and
a deep draught close to the shore, allowing big ships to come in.
</P>
<P>
The SDA was set up by the government to oversee development of
the long-neglected south, which has rich untapped natural
resources as well as an educated workforce.
</P>
<P>
The government is keen to accelerate development of the region
where unemployment levels are higher than the national average.
</P>
</TEXT>
