<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chemical Industry Faces Fierce Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Surging demand and anticipated
fierce international competition are prompting China's chemical
industry to chart its course for growth as the 21st century nears,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The outline of the Tenth Five-Year Plan (2001-2005) of the
Ministry of Chemical Industry (MCI) which is being drawn up covers
five priority sectors-- agrichemicals, petrochemicals, fine
chemicals, rubber processing and chemical projects related to
energy-efficiency and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
A MCI statement said the drafting of the plan is in line with
four principles in selecting processes: sectors and products that
fall short of demand sharply but have a large market potential;
sectors and products that are vital to the national economy but in
short supply; sectors and products with high technology content;
and sectors and products that are expected to be good candidates
for export.
</P>
<P>
MCI minister Gu Xiulian urged the enterprises operating under
its umbrella to form alliances to combat increasing challenges
both from joint ventures and foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
She also suggested that a broad sales network and concentrated
system for materials procurement be established to link the
related industrial sectors together.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of this year, the total output of
the industry increased a year-on-year 8.7 percent. Exports jumped
up 20.3 percent from the first nine months in 1996 to enable the
trade deficit in the industry to fall 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that sales of the industry will hit 300 billion
yuan this year, and profits will reach 2 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
