<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Urged to Lead in Greenhouse Gas Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have agreed that developed
countries should play a leading role in reducing greenhouse gases,
a Thai environment official said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN environment ministers have met in Indonesia recently,
urging developed countries to honor their commitments rather than
trying to force developing countries to cut back greenhouse gas
emissions, Wanee Samphantharak, deputy secretary-general of the
environment policy and planning office, told reporters over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The cost for cutting back greenhouse gas emissions would be too
high for developing countries, Wanee said.
</P>
<P>
However, the official noted that ASEAN countries including
Thailand have agreed to reduce greenhouse gases on a voluntary
basis.
</P>
<P>
Suvit Yodmanee of the United Nations Environment Program also
said that it would be difficult to force developing countries to
cut greenhouse emissions.
</P>
<P>
The developed countries were the main sources of greenhouse
gases because of their decades of industrial development, Suvit
noted.
</P>
<P>
Every country should make efforts to help reduce greenhouse
gases, but developed countries should play a leading role, Suvit
said.  
</P>
