<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rate Cut Good for Renminbi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The latest interest rate cut
will help China prevent international speculators from taking
advantage of rate differences between the yuan and foreign
currencies, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
As the interest rate of the country's one-year term deposits
dropped to 5.67 percent, there is only a 0.5 percentage gap
between the yuan and the interest rate of the US dollar, said Tao
Liming, director of the Institute of International Finance of the
Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the yuan and US dollar was more than two
percentage points before the rate was cut. As the yuan's exchange
rate against the US dollar has remained stable the past three
years, the recent large gap resulted in some unbalanced fund flow
to currencies with higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Tao said that easing the influx of foreign speculative funds
will help somewhat relieve the strong appreciation pressures on
the renminbi.
</P>
<P>
He said an over-strong renminbi will adversely affect the
competitiveness of Chinese exporters. If the country's exports
drop, the operation of some State-owned enterprises and the
overall economic development would also be adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
And if appreciation pressure on the renminbi become too strong,
the central bank will be forced to issue more yuan to stabilize
the exchange rate, which could undermine the stability of the
bank's monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Tao said that China can avoid the currency upheaval that hit
southeast Asian countries last summer as China has not released
its foreign exchange control over capital accounts and also enjoys
a more favorable macro-economic situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
