<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Launch Plan to Fight Arsenic Contamination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
launch an emergency program to provide safe drinking water to
people in 200 of the villages worst affected by arsenic
contamination of ground water, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The program will cover 22 southwestern districts where people
have been identified with "symptoms of chronic arsenic poisoning."
</P>
<P>
The six-month program will serve as a model one and a long-term
program will be formulated to address the "national disaster,"
declared by the government in May.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-financed 300,000 U.S. dollar program will implemented
jointly by government agencies and some local non-government
organizations.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1,800 confirmed cases of arsenicosis across the
country and a large number of people in at least 60 districts are
at risk.
</P>
<P>
Experts said arsenicosis causes malonosis and that the ultimate
result is tissue mutation which may cause cancer, but not in all
cases.
</P>
<P>
Arsenic contamination of ground water was first detected in
Bangladesh in August last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
