<HEADLINE> CCPIT to Develop New Trade Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The China Council for the
Promotion of International Trade (CCPIT) will do more to diversify
the country's foreign trade and serve all the firms in China,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Central America, South America, the Gulf Region and Africa will
be the focus of CCPIT's promotion work, said Yu Xiaosong, the new
CCPIT chairman and also chairman of the China Chamber of
International Commerce (CCOIC).
</P>
<P>
He said China's trade with those regions makes up less than two
percent of the total trade volume for the areas. Therefore, great
market potential remains to be tapped, the new chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Promotion work in Central America is especially needed, as
China has not established diplomatic ties with most of the Central
American countries, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
He said CCPIT will present Chinese commodity fairs in Panama
and South Africa this month.
</P>
<P>
As for trade across the Taiwan Straits, Yu said CCPIT will do
more exchange work with Taiwan to help realize direct shipping,
postal and commercial links.
</P>
<P>
He urged Taiwan authorities to re-consider their restrictive
policies about across-the-straits trade and Taiwan investment in
the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Yu said a CCPIT delegation, headed by Vice-Chairman An
Chengxin, will visit Taiwan in December.
</P>
<P>
As for serving enterprises in China, CCPIT and CCOIC will face
more challenges as trade liberalization progresses, the chairman
said.
</P>
<P>
Not counting foreign trade houses, more than 6,000
manufacturers and research institutes, and about 140,000
foreign-funded enterprises, have been granted foreign trade rights.
</P>
<P>
China also promised to consolidate the foreign trade
registration system, replacing the present approval system, by
2000.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, CCPIT and CCOIC will have to work harder to
establish relations with tens of thousands of enterprises in the
country and provide better services for them, Yu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
