<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Myanmar to Develop Downstream Wood Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 2 (Xinhua) -- the Myanmar timber authorities
are making efforts to gradually phase out log sales in the coming
years and develop its downstream industries for value-added
products.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Myanmar Timber Enterprise (MTE) under the
Ministry of Forestry, plans to convert saw mills into integrated
industries to produce a combination of high value sawn timber and
downstream value-added products, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
More furniture and moulding factories will also be set up to
make maximum use of the semi-finished products from the upstream
industries.
</P>
<P>
As an initial move towards going downstream, the MTE is
cooperating with foreign companies in establishing direct
investment or joint ventures to turn out value-added products.
</P>
<P>
Seven foreign firms from China, France, South Korea, Malaysia,
Norway and Thailand have signed business agreements with the MTE,
setting up plywood, moulding and furniture factories in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Domestic private companies in the manufacturing business buy
logs and sawn timber from the MTE for further processing and
distribution of their products in the domestic market and for
export.
</P>
<P>
The MTE is the sole organization allowed to extract timber out
of forests in Myanmar and it undertakes logging, transportation,
milling, processing, distribution of products within the country,
and exportation.
</P>
<P>
In its efforts to stop the export of teak and other hardwood
logs, Myanmar plans to establish two international-level
wood-based industry zones in the capital of Yangon to boost the
manufacture of value-added finished wood products.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also plans to undertake the projects for introducing
Myanmar's lesser-used timber species to the world market and
upgrading production efficiency in furniture manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's hardwood export in
the 1996-97 fiscal year ending March was 209,137 cubic meters,
while the export of teak was 196,260 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The country's export of forest products amounted to 218 million
U.S. dollars in 1996-97, accounting for 24.4 percent of the total
export, second only to the export of agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar restricts export of logs and bans the private sector
from exporting teak logs after the enactment of the country's
Forest Law in 1992. However, export of value-added wood products
is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in forest resources with forests covering about
51 percent of its land area. The country has been planting 37,260
hectares of forest annually since the 1992-93 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The total area of forest plantations established from 1963 to
1996 has reached 524,000 hectares, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two New Zealand firms have been carrying out pilot
projects on tree plantations in Myanmar's Shan state since early
last year and a Japan-based non-governmental organization, the
Organization for industrial, Spiritual and Cultural
Advancement-International, also plans to establish agro-forests in
the country's Magway division.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0144 </DOCNO>
