<HEADLINE> Italy: Pensions Agreement Paves Way for 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government reached an
agreement with trade unions today to save 4 trillion lire (about
2.3 billion U.S. dollars) from the national pensions program.
</P>
<P>
Although it is still an agreement in principle, the latest move
is hailed by observers here as the removal of a major hurdle to
the approval of the government's 1998 budget plan.
</P>
<P>
While the two sides are working on details of the measure, the
government is expected to file an amendment of welfare expenditure
to the financial bill for 1998 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The unions will endorse the overall cost reduction agreement,
crucial for Italy's entry into the single European currency union,
when it is approved by union members.
</P>
<P>
Fausto Bertinotti, leader of the Communist Refoundation, said
he believed that the agreement will lead to a reduction in
disparities of pension treatment.
</P>
<P>
