<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis May Spur Global Depression: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The massive loss of confidence
in the global capital market could lead to worldwide economic
depression unless the economic and currency crisis in Southeast
Asia is properly addressed, a Thai economist said.
</P>
<P>
Somkiat Osotsapa, an economist at Thailand's Chulalongkorn
University, said a crisis in one region could affect markets all
over the world because economies have become more globally
integrated.
</P>
<P>
Since the July 2 Thai baht floatation, the Malaysian ringgit,
Philippine peso and Indonesian rupiah have tumbled along with the
baht, and Indonesia has also had to accept an International
Monetary Fund rescue package.
</P>
<P>
The contagion has spread to East Asia, causing the South Korean
won to plunge. The Hong Kong dollar is also under pressure from
money speculators.
</P>
<P>
"When the baht broke through the 40 baht to the dollar barrier,
it entered into a free fall which Thailand by itself cannot stop,
which will cause Southeast Asian currencies to fall further,
inflicting serious damage to economies across the region," Somkiat
was quoted as saying by the local press.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the baht could sink to 50 to the dollars, a 100
percent drop in value from the pre-float era. Regional problems
could also affect Japanese multinational corporations and banks
which have invested heavily in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Somkiat predicted that the problem would spread to other
financial markets if Japanese firms repatriate their funds to help
their subsidiaries in Southeast Asia stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
One could imagine the damage to the U.S. financial sector, the
dollar's strength and real economic health if the Japanese give up
their stock and bond holdings in the U.S., as America is the
world's biggest debtor nation with debts estimated at 860 billion
dollars, most of it owed to Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trouble in Asia will certainly hurt U.S. exports to the region,
lead to the slowdown of corporate earning and then damage the U.S.
stock and banking sectors, he said. European exports to Asia would
also drop and EU corporations in the region could not escape
without losing, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. and Europe have to take seriously the bailout of the
Southeast Asian region by offering enough funds and markets open
to import products, in order to prevent the problem from getting
out of hand," Somkiat said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. should also consider opening its markets to more
exports from the region and support the creation of the Asian
Monetary Fund as well as increase regulation on hedge funds which
destabilize regional currencies, Somkiat said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
