<HEADLINE> China's State Sector May Open to Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- China's troublesome state
sector is likely to open to foreign investment, according to
today's Business Weekly of the Beijing-based English newspaper
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government is weighing policies allowing foreign
investors to merge, lease or buy out China's medium and small
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are showing great interest in China's ongoing
reforms of its state sector, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
The participation of foreign investors in reforming the State
sector will help improve Chinese firms' management and technology,
change their operational mechanism and speed the accretion of
their assets, said Xia Youfu, professor of the Chinese University
of International Business and Economics and president of the Gear
Development Center for International Trade and Investment. He
noted that many of the country's about 100,000 Sino-foreign joint
ventures involve state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
However, Xia cautioned that the State should make appropriete
policies to prevent the negative aspects of such massive
co-operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
