<HEADLINE> Polish New Cabinet Stressing Social Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The new Polish cabinet is
orienting toward a series of social reforms to restructure the
country's health care, education and social security systems.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek, appointed by President Alexander
Kwasniewski two weeks ago and operative from Saturday, made his
priorities clear at the first meeting of cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Buzek was quoted as saying by a Polish Press Agency report that
his cabinet would decentralize the country's fiscal process to
separate the state and local controls over public financing.
</P>
<P>
While some authority would be granted to local autonomies, he
said, many state businesses would be privatized to help improve
the industrial output, especially by the mining sector.
</P>
<P>
Poland's bid for an early entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU) has a priority on
the new cabinet's agenda, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Buzek, of a political coalition winning the parliamentary
election in September, assumed the premiership after his
predecessor Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz resigned on October 17.
</P>
