<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cotton Importers Warned of Quality Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration of
Import and Export Commodities Inspection (SACI) has sounded an
alarm for the domestic cotton industry, today's China Daily
reported .
</P>
<P>
SACI has called the attention of business people in the
industry and related authorities to the problems of imported
cotton and measures to curb those problems.
</P>
<P>
According to China's customs statistics, some 460,000 tons of
cotton, worth 808 million US dollars, were imported in the first
half of this year, a 14 percent hike from last year.
</P>
<P>
However, many of those imports have quality or quantity
problems, especially from the United States, SACI said in a
written statement last week.
</P>
<P>
Of the 788 batches of cotton imported in the period, 89 percent
proved to be substandard, which was two percentage points higher
than last year.
</P>
<P>
Besides the poor quality, more and more cotton imports are not
as heavy as claimed, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The customs statistics indicate China imported 1.1 million tons
of cotton in the past year and a half. However, only 960,000 tons
were examined by SACI.
</P>
<P>
The problems of imported cotton have greatly hurt the interest
of Chinese cotton farmers and business people, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
SACI suggests that the quality of domestically produced cotton
be upgraded and its distribution network be improved to narrow the
price gap between domestic and foreign cotton.
</P>
<P>
It also advises importers or end-users make clear in their
importing contracts that transactions should be based on SACI's
inspection results and consign the inspection of the imported
cotton to SACT's overseas branches to prevent more losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Surplus to Shrink in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- China's expected 20 billion US
dollars trade surplus this year will not repeat itself in 1998,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Although China's foreign trade surplus hit 30.6 billion US
dollars in the first three quarters of this year, the imports will
post a moderate growth in the remaining months of this year, which
will not reduce the surplus by a large margin, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Jian, senior researcher under the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation, next year will witness a
much smaller surplus as a result of China's recent tariff slash,
interest rate cut and the tariff exemption for imports of capital
goods by foreign-funded high-tech firms, expected to be announced
next year.
</P>
<P>
When China's average tariff level was reduced to 17 percent
from 23 percent on October 1, it stimulated imports, and this
effect will be appreciable next year, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate cut, which was announced two weeks ago, will
surely stimulate domestic consumption and investment, and hence
bolster the demand for more imports.
</P>
<P>
Another major incentive for more imports will be the resumption
of free duty on imports of capital goods for high-tech projects,
which would be carried out in the first half of next year.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed to China's ongoing technology renovations in
State-owned enterprises and development of the high-tech industry
as major recipients of the increased imports.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, imports of raw materials, such as crude oil
and other natural resources, will grow, as China's production of
those raw materials can not meet the demand of its rapid economic
development, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that as the country's bid for admission into the
World Trade Organization progresses, China's import regime will
also be improved, which will be conducive to more imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid to Indonesia Expected to Exceed 37 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The financial aid pledged to
revive confidence in Indonesia's economy could exceed 37 billion
U.S. dollars, sources at the Indonesian Finance Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
The assistance comprises 14 billion dollars from Asian
countries and the United States and an International Monetary Fund
(IMF) assistance package valued at 23 billion dollars, said the
sources today.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Finance Minister Richard Hu and Japan's vice finance
minister Eisuke Sakakibara met with Indonesian Finance Minister
Mar'ie Muhammad here Saturday and pledged to extend up to 5
billion dollars respectively, in stand-by loans, to Indonesia,
said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Hu and Sakakibara expressed their concern over the excessive
depreciation of the Indonesian currency although Indonesia's
economic fundamentals are sound.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah has dropped by about 50 percent this
year after being badly hit by the current monetary crisis in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of the financial aid could go up to 38 billion
dollars as Malaysian Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim has also
pledged one billion dollars in a stand-by loan, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is much higher than the 17.2 billion dollars
extended to Thailand, recently hard hit by the currency crisis
that was followed by a worsening political situation at home.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government announced a reform package on October
31 aimed at restoring a macroeconomic stability badly battered by
the recent monetary and confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform package, the government will slash budget
outlay, curtail monopolies in several food commodities and
liquidate insolvent banks. Indonesia began implementing the reform
package Saturday, with the liquidation of 16 financially troubled
private banks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
