<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Art Markets Prosperous in Changsha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Visitors touring Changsha,
capital of central China's Hunan Province, are likely to be as
attracted to the abundant art markets as to local scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
But the markets, which sell diverse traditional handicrafts,
calligraphy and paintings as well as copies of oil masterpieces,
aren't for tourists alone: Changsha residents keen on enriching
their lives are spending more on high-priced cultural items like
musical instruments, art and flowers.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the statistics bureau in Changsha in 1996
showed that 35 out of every 100 households own an expensive
musical instrument, and cultural entertainment claims an average
15 percent of the monthly income of each household.
</P>
<P>
As a result, culture-oriented shops have sprung up all over
town in the past few years, predominantly galleries and flower
shops.
</P>
<P>
The Jingdian Art Shop, situated in an alley known as "Street of
Artwork," has been successfully managed by several young men.
</P>
<P>
"A few years ago, people began to want to buy art for wedding
gifts, such as Hunan embroidery, a renowned traditional handicraft
item in Hunan, but hunted in local shops in vain," one of the
managers said. "My friends and I seized the trend and invested in
this business."
</P>
<P>
Pointing to a piece embroidered with mountains and rivers, he
said, "This one costs 500 to 600 yuan, a rather high price, but
people are spending more decorating their rooms. This kind of art
is favored by young people. We can sell ten pieces of this kind
every day."
</P>
<P>
Sociologists theorize that the increasing interest in the
expensive artwork may be just a fad now, but they hope it will
encourage people to seek a more advanced cultural level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
