<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Forestry, Livestock, Farm Exports Up 1.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Chile's export earnings from
forestry, livestock and farm produce in the first nine months of
the year were up 1.7 percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase prompted the sector's total exports to 3.333
billion U.S. dollars in the nine-month period, said the
Agriculture Ministry's Agrarian Studies and Policies Office.
</P>
<P>
The exports combined with imports worth 872 million dollars to
result in a foreign trade surplus of 2.461 billion dollars for the
sector, 2.7 percent more than that of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By subsector, forestry exports increased by 5.4 percent to 1.26
billion dollars, making it the biggest foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the highest overseas sales growth was reported by
wines and liquors with a 50.1 percent rise to 303 million dollars;
and by cattle, with a 45.6 percent gain to 126 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the total earnings from fruits dropped 8.4 percent and
those of fresh fruits down by 4.7 percent after a drought hit the
country's central area in the 1996-97 farm season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
