<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> d p s 3075 China-Three Gorges-Construction Three Gorges Project Creates Man-made Miracles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING (Three Gorges), November 2 (Xinhua) -- Construction
workers of the gigantic Three Gorges Project had moved 22.4
million cubic meters of soil and hard rock away, and mixed and
poured about 160,000 cubic meters of concrete for the construction
of the man-made canal alone.
</P>
<P>
During the past four years, or the first-phase construction of the
giant project, certain big pre-damming projects create man-made
miracles in the engineering construction history of China. The
man-made Yangtze is one of them.
</P>
<P>
To dam the Yangtze River while ensuring the smooth navigation
in this China's busiest river channel after the damming,
developers of the Three Gorges Project dug the canal along
the north bank of this world's third longest river.
</P>
<P>
The open-cut canal, or the water diversion channel, is 3,410 meters
long and 350 meters wide at the bottom. The height of the canal's
dikes hit 58 meters.
</P>
<P>
This "man-made Yangtze" is designed to be capable of combating
against strong flood. In peak flood season, the canal can divert
flood water at 79,000 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Water of the Yangtze first flew through the canal last May. Up to
October 30, some 6,400 vessels had passed the canal since it's
opened to traffic on October 5.
</P>
<P>
After the third-phase construction between 2004 and 2009, the
canal will be blocked, on which the north-bank hydro-power plant
will be built.
</P>
<P>
Another big, and one of the hardest projects, in the
construction of the massive Three Gorges Project, is the erection
of permanent ship locks.
</P>
<P>
In the north-bank construction site, a man-made "grand canyon",
where ships will sail along when the dam is built, has taken shape
on the granite slopes. The 3,800-meter-long, 300-meter-wide canyon
will eventually be turned out to be the permanent ship lock, the
largest to be built in the world.
</P>
<P>
Sandouping, widely described as an ideal dam site for a large
water project, is wholly grounded on granite, the hardest rock.
</P>
<P>
The firmest foundation for the dam, however, posed hardest
challenges for developers. It will a decade to complete this
single project. Soil and rock dug for the permanent ship lock
account to 40 percent of the total amount of the entire Three
Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, most of the digging work has been finished and the
five-level lock rooms have taken shape.
</P>
<P>
The third big project in the first-phase is to start the
construction of the temporary ship lock and ship lifts,
which facilitate navigation in flood seasons.
</P>
<P>
In the flood season, the flow velocity in the open-cut canal
may exceed 20,000 cubic meters per second, too fast for ships to
pass. To ensure the year-round operation on this busy water
channel, developers have worked hard to speed up the construction
of temporary ship locks and ship-lifts.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the channel of the temporary ship lock, with a
height of 130 meters, has been cut from the granite slope.
Builders are seen installing mental structures at the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
