<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project to Cost Over 200 billion Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING (Three Gorges), November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Three
Gorges Project was estimated to require a 90-billion-yuan
investment based on 1993 constant prices, but inflation and
expenditures increased the cost projections to more than 200 billion
yuan (about 24 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the huge amount, the investment is equivalent to just
0.123 percent of the gross domestic production (GDP) and 0.98
percent of the cumulative capital construction investment across
China during the 17 years of construction.
</P>
<P>
Funds for the project come from the following sources:
</P>
<P>
-- A Three Gorges Construction Fund based on appropriation from
electricity charges across China;
</P>
<P>
-- All sales income from electricity generated by the Gezhouba
Power Plant, which is also owned by China Yangtze Three Gorges
Project Development Corp.;
</P>
<P>
-- Profits from the Three Gorges power station when it goes
into operation in the year of 2003;
</P>
<P>
-- Loans from the State Development Bank and domestic
commercial banks;
</P>
<P>
-- Bonds issued both at home and overseas and;
</P>
<P>
-- Export credit loans and commercial loans from foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Financing of the project will go through three stages.
</P>
<P>
The first stage will be purely input from 1993-2005; a balance
between revenue and expenses is expected to be reached in 2006,
with no further need to borrow.
</P>
<P>
The second will a debt-repayment period from 2006 to 2012. And
from 2012 on the project is expected to make a pure profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0199 </DOCNO>
