<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Luther King Jr.' Heir Named to Lead Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Southern Christian
Leadership Conference (SCLC) delegates have elected Martin Luther
King III to head the organization of his father, the slain civil
rights leader, founded in 1957.
</P>
<P>
In a special convention at the historic Ebenezer Baptist Church
in Atlanta, King, 40, was unanimously elected the fourth president
of the grassroots civil rights group, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
King, a former Fulton County, Georgia, commissioner, will
replace Reverend Joseph Lowery, who announced his retirement
earlier this year, but agreed to stay on until a successor was
named.
</P>
<P>
King told delegates from SCLC chapters and affiliates across
the country, "We've made many strides since the inception of SCLC
40 years ago, but as an organization and a nation, we have so much
further to go."
</P>
<P>
King said in his acceptance speech he would be a "tireless
steward" of the organization.
</P>
<P>
King was the second of the four children. Like his siblings, he
felt the sting of segregation. In 1963, he was denied admission to
Atlanta's private Lovett School because he was black, according to
reports.
</P>
<P>
The SCLC was founded by Lowery, Martin Luther King Jr., Ralph
David Abernathy Sr., and others. Lowery has served as its
president since 1977, when he succeeded Abernathy, who took over
after the 1968 assassination of Martin Luther King Jr., the
organization's first president.
</P>
<P>
Lowery says King has his full support. King will officially
become SCLC president on Jan. 15, 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
