<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang Says His U.S. Visit Is a Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOSTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said his trip to the United States has produced important results
in enhancing mutual understanding between China and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who flew in this morning from New York to continue his
nine-day state visit to the U.S., the first by a Chinese President
in 12 years, told a luncheon today that his talks with President
Bill Clinton reached understanding on a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
The luncheon was hosted by Massachusetts Governor Paul Celluci
and Boston Mayor Thomas Menino in honor of Jiang who earlier
delivered a speech in Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton and I agreed that the U.S. and China should
strengthen cooperation and make efforts to build a constructive
strategic relationship in view of the 21st century for the lofty
cause of enhancing world peace and development," Jiang told an
audience of over 200.
</P>
<P>
Long seen as the birthplace of the American industrial
revolution, Massachusetts has a long history of exchanges with
China, Jiang said, adding that Chinese students' footmarks can be
traced back to the first days of this century.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Jiang said, bilateral exchanges and
cooperation have expanded to cover more areas including economic
and trade, technical and scientific, education, culture, financing
and insurance.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his hope to see more people from the state to visit
China, to invest there and to develop trade, Jiang said
Massachusetts can play an active role in promoting bilateral ties
as it is advantageous in high-tech, medical and insurance fields.
</P>
<P>
Celluci and Menino also spoke of their willingness to enhance
cooperation between Massachusetts, Boston and China.
</P>
<P>
Earlier President Jiang met and conducted cordial conversations
with them.
</P>
<P>
Jiang started his U.S. journey on October 26 at the invitation
of President Clinton. He and his entourage left Boston this
afternoon for Los Angeles, the last leg of the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
