<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Astrophysicist Found New Moons of Uranus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 1 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian astrophysicist has
found two new moons circling the planet Uranus, a report said
today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the moons' existence was made Friday to the
world's astronomical community after a second group of sightings
had confirmed their existence.
</P>
<P>
This brings to 17 the number of known Uranian moons, according
to today's Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Brett Gladman, a postdoctoral fellow at the Institute for
Theoretical Astrophysics in Toronto located the two moons at the
beginning of last month.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gladman, 31, believes that the finding of these two
smallish bodies -- one roughly 80 kilometers in diameter and the
other about 160 kilometers -- raises the possibility that up to
another dozen rocky bits of material may be circling the giant
planet.
</P>
<P>
The moons were found almost by chance using the 200-inch Hale
Telescope in Palomar, California.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gladman was using the telescope to search for comets in
conjunction with Phillip Nicholson and Joseph Burns of Cornell
University and J.J. Kavelaars of McMaster University.
</P>
<P>
There was an hour or so of observing time that was not suitable
for the cometary research, so Prof. Nicholson suggested a look at
an area around Uranus where moons might be present. Then came the
finding.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gladman will get to name one of the moons, while the other
will be named by Prof. Nicholson, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
