<DOCNO> XIE19971102.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Want Government to Cut Debt, Taxes, Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Canadians want
the government to focus on tax and debt reduction after
eliminating the deficit, according to a poll published today.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail/Angus Reid poll found that only 13 percent
Canadians felt that increasing spending should be the top
priority.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven percent of those surveyed said that the government
should make efforts to reduce the country's 600 billion dollar
(430 billion USD) debt and to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
"This would appear to represent a fundamental change in public
opinion," said the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
As recently as February, an Angus Reid poll found nine percent
of Canadians wanted government to meet its deficit target and put
any extra cash toward a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
The most favored option at that time was for the government to
spend more on health and education. This time, increased spending
ranked a distant third on the list of preferences.
</P>
<P>
"There was a very good job done by the Reform and the
Progressive Conservatives (parties) during the (Spring) election
campaign to give some momentum behind the whole tax-cut issues,"
said Darrell Bricker, senior vice president of the Angus Reid
Group.
</P>
<P>
In terms of specific tax reductions, a majority of those polled
indicated the government should first cut the goods and services
tax, compared with 37 percent who said an income-tax cut should
take precedence and 10 percent who favored lowering unemployment
insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,515 adult Canadians was conducted between
October 23 and 28. Its results are considered to be accurate
within 2.5 percentage points 19 times out of 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
